    <main class="container">
    <section id="penguins">
    <h2>All About Penguins!</h2>
    <div class="row">
    <article class="col-sm">
    <h3>Macaroni Penguin</h3>
    <figure>
        <a href="images/macaroni_large.jpg">
        <img src="https://raw.github.com/n1qlvs/image-hosting/main/BOTW-Homepage-Thumbnail_Macaroni-Penguins_JCTravelography_Shutterstock.jpg" alt="Macaroni Penguin" class="img-fluid"
        title="View larger image..."/>
        </a>
        <figcaption>Macaroni Penguin</figcaption>
    </figure>
        
    <p>
        The Macaroni penguin is a species of penguin found from the Subantarctic to the Antarctic Peninsula. It is characterized by its distinctive yellow-orange crest and black-and-white plumage. These penguins are excellent swimmers and primarily feed on krill and other small marine creatures.
    </p>
    </article>

    <article class="col-sm">
    <h3>African Penguin</h3>
    <figure>
        <a href="images/african_large.jpg">
        <img src="https://raw.github.com/n1qlvs/image-hosting/main/penguin_01.jpg" alt="African Penguin" class="img-fluid"
        title="View larger image..."/>
        </a>
        <figcaption>African Penguin</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
        The African penguin is a species native to the coasts of southern Africa. They are well adapted to warmer climates and are known for their loud, donkey-like braying calls. These penguins are currently endangered due to habitat destruction and declining fish populations.
    </p>
    </article>
    </div>
    </section>

    <section id="arctic-foxes">
        <h2>All About Arctic Foxes!</h2>
        <div class="row">
        <article class="col-sm">
        <h3>White Morph Arctic Fox</h3>
        <figure>
            <a href="images/white_morph_large.jpg">
            <img src="https://raw.github.com/n1qlvs/image-hosting/main/arctic-fox-468029675-5b3247a0c9e77c001a4df47a.jpg" alt="White Morph Arctic Fox" class="img-fluid"
            title="View larger image..."/>
            </a>
            <figcaption>White Morph Arctic Fox</figcaption>
        </figure>
            
        <p>
            The White Morph Arctic Fox is the more common variant of the Arctic fox. It has a thick white coat in winter, which helps it blend into snowy environments, and turns brownish-gray in summer. These foxes are well adapted to extreme cold and can survive in harsh Arctic conditions.
        </p>
        </article>

        <article class="col-sm">
        <h3>Blue Morph Arctic Fox</h3>
        <figure>
            <a href="images/blue_morph_large.jpg">
            <img src="https://raw.github.com/n1qlvs/image-hosting/main/9d697b6a0c18202d8283edb6f5389133.jpg" alt="Blue Morph Arctic Fox" class="img-fluid"
            title="View larger image..."/>
            </a>
            <figcaption>Blue Morph Arctic Fox</figcaption> 
        </figure>
        <p>
            The Blue Morph Arctic Fox is a rarer variation of the Arctic fox, featuring a dark bluish-gray coat year-round. Unlike the white morph, it does not change color with the seasons. This variation is more commonly found in coastal areas, where it blends in with rocky shorelines rather than snow.
        </p>
        </article>
        </div>
        </section>

